29. 22. quoniam: the Mss. read cum, which is impossible here. Lambinus conjectured quod, adopted by Miiller. 1 have adopted Reid’ s conjecture, quoniam, believing that Cicero would hardly have written quod id quod. Assuming that Cicero wrote quoniam, we have only to suppose that this became corrupted to quom (an easy change, especially as quoniam was often abbreviated as fin). Cicero probably regularly wrote quom ior the conjunction. The copyists have changed this regularly to cum. Hence the Ms. cum in the present passage could easily go back (through quom) to an original quoniam, as conjectured by Reid. Hale, Cum-Construc- tions, p. 243 (German ed. p. 302), defends the Ms. reading cum.
